</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Foreign objects are not infrequently seen at computed tomography (CT) of the abdomen and pelvis and may pose a diagnostic challenge to the radiologist, who must recognize the object, characterize its nature and location, and determine its clinical significance. Most foreign objects are incidentally detected at CT, but they may mimic a wide range of pathologic conditions. Some foreign objects (eg, an object that has been swallowed either intentionally or unintentionally) are the cause of the patient's signs and symptoms and require prompt medical attention. Other objects, such as a sponge or surgical instrument that has been retained postoperatively, may have medicolegal consequences. Furthermore, certain objects, such as intentionally concealed drug packets, may go undetected unless a high degree of suspicion exists and appropriate window settings are used to review the study. The radiologist should be familiar with the wide range of foreign objects that may be encountered at abdominopelvic CT, be able to recognize them promptly, and understand their implications for patient treatment.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2011</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.312105123">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.312105123">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig01.jpeg" height="1292" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Bezoar causing small bowel obstruction in a patient with no prior history of abdominal surgery. Contrast material–enhanced CT scan through the abdomen shows a bezoar with a mottled appearance (arrow) at the transition zone (arrowhead) of a small bowel obstruction. Subsequent laparotomy and enterotomy revealed a partially digested vegetable (possibly a cucumber or a date) lodged in the bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig02.jpeg" height="1674" width="1674" aria-labelledby="fig02" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Small bowel feces in a patient with adhesive small bowel obstruction. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a distended small bowel loop (arrow) containing particulate material mixed with gas bubbles. A transition zone (arrowhead) is noted distal to the small bowel feces. Small bowel feces appear more amorphous and affect longer segments compared with a small bowel bezoar, which appears as a well-defined, focal, ovoid mass with a mottled gas pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig02">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig03a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1667" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig03b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1572" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig04a.jpeg" height="1548" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig04b.jpeg" height="1346" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig05.jpeg" height="1640" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig05" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span> Small bowel obstruction caused by a dislodged feeding tube. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image demonstrates the distal inflated balloon of a dislodged feeding tube (arrowhead) and the coiled proximal portion of the tube in the terminal ileum (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig05">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig06.jpeg" height="1312" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Detached pH meter capsule. Coronal contrast-enhanced CT scan demonstrates a disposable pH meter capsule (arrow) in the small bowel. The capsule had become detached from the esophagus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig07.jpeg" height="1590" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig07" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span> Impacted endoscopic capsule. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image clearly depicts an impacted endoscopic capsule (arrow) at a stricture in the terminal ileum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig07">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig08.jpeg" height="1600" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Intestinal perforation caused by an intraluminal fish bone. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows a fish bone (arrow) adjacent to the wall in a bowel loop. The pericolonic fat is slightly infiltrated. Subsequent images revealed that the tip of the bone had penetrated the bowel wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig09.jpeg" height="1486" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Accidentally swallowed needle. Noncontrast CT scan obtained 16 hours after the patient had accidentally swallowed a sewing needle clearly depicts the needle (arrow) in the small bowel lumen, with no evidence of bowel perforation.z<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig10.jpeg" height="1090" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Ingested batteries. Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows multiple small, round, high-attenuation structures (arrow) in the stomach. Urgent endoscopy was performed, and eight watch batteries were removed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig11a.jpeg" height="1051" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig11b.jpeg" height="1125" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig12a.jpeg" height="1282" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig12b.jpeg" height="1295" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig13.jpeg" height="1256" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Concealed narcotics. Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a well-defined tubular object (arrow) in the rectum. The object proved to be a packet of narcotics that was being smuggled. Use of greater window width allows better recognition of foreign bodies in the gastrointestinal tract.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig14.jpeg" height="1192" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Abdominal wall mesh. Contrast-enhanced CT scan demonstrates an abdominal wall mesh (arrow) that had been used to repair a ventral hernia. Note that the mesh is held in place with multiple metallic structures along the periphery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig15.jpeg" height="1224" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Mesh plugs. Contrast-enhanced CT scan demonstrates bilateral round soft-tissue masses (arrows) at the internal ring of the inguinal canal. These findings are compatible with mesh plugs that had been used for bilateral herniorrhaphy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig16.jpeg" height="1379" width="1584" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Retained gallstones resulting in abscess formation. Noncontrast CT scan obtained 3 weeks after surgery shows a retained gallstone (arrow) that has led to an inflammatory response with abscess formation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig17.jpeg" height="1513" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Gallstone spillage. Contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained at the level of the uterus shows multiple round soft-tissue nodules with a high-attenuation peripheral rim (arrows). These findings may sometimes be mistaken for calcifying metastatic implants; in this case, however, a review of findings from previous studies revealed that these nodules represent gallstones that appeared shortly after laparoscopic cholecystectomy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig18a.jpeg" height="1244" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig18b.jpeg" height="1236" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig19a.jpeg" height="1347" width="1620" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig19b.jpeg" height="1743" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig20a.jpeg" height="1267" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig20a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig20b.jpeg" height="1338" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig20b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig21.jpeg" height="846" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig21" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21</span> Urethral bulking agent. Coronal reformatted contrast-enhanced CT image shows high-attenuation microbeads (arrow), which were used as a urethral bulking agent.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig21">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig22a.jpeg" height="1321" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig22a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig22b.jpeg" height="1328" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig22b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig23a.jpeg" height="1305" width="1530" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig23b.jpeg" height="1558" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig24a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1763" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig24b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1703" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig25" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig25.jpeg" height="1402" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig25" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 25</span> Bogota bag. Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a Bogota bag (arrows) as a curvilinear high-attenuation area. Bogota bags are used to provide temporary abdominal closure, usually along the anterior abdominal wall.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig25">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig26" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig26.jpeg" height="918" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig26" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 26</span> Heterotopic mesenteric ossification. Coronal reformatted noncontrast CT images from three different studies demonstrate the rapid development (left to right) of extensive high-attenuation linear-branching structures (arrow) in the mesentery of the small bowel, findings that are characteristic of heterotopic mesenteric ossification. Awareness of this entity is crucial if one is to avoid confusing it with oral contrast material extravasation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig26">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig27a.jpeg" height="1547" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig27a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig27b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig27b.jpeg" height="1397" width="1584" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 27b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig27b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig28a.jpeg" height="1176" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig28a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig28b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig28b.jpeg" height="1256" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 28b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig28b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig29" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.312105123/asset/images/105123fig29.jpeg" height="1476" width="1295" aria-labelledby="fig29" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 29</span> Failed renal transplant mimicking a mass. Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows a partially calcified soft-tissue mass (arrow) in the extraperitoneal right lower quadrant, a finding that represents a rejected renal transplant. The mass lacks the morphologic features and size of a normal functioning renal transplant.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.312105123&amp;id=fig29">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">O'Connor AR, Coakley FV, Meng MV, Eberhardt SC. Imaging of retained surgical sponges in the abdomen and pelvis. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2003;180(2):481–489.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.2214/ajr.180.2.1800481">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12540456/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Imaging+of+retained+surgical+sponges+in+the+abdomen+and+pelvis&amp;author=AR+O%27Connor&amp;author=FV+Coakley&amp;author=MV+Meng&amp;author=SC+Eberhardt&amp;publication_year=2003&amp;journal=AJR+Am+J+Roentgenol&amp;pages=481-489&amp;doi=10.2214%2Fajr.180.2.1800481&amp;pmid=12540456">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Gayer G, Jonas T, Apter S, et al. Bezoars in the stomach and small bowel: CT appearance. <em>Clin Radiol</em> 1999;54(4):228–232.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/S0009-9260(99)91156-X">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="htt